# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gitignore-patterns
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In computing, a **directory** is a file system cataloging structure that contains references to other computer files, and possibly other directories.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] On many computers, directories are known as **folders** or **drawers**, analogous to a workbench or the traditional office filing cabinet.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The name derives from books like a telephone directory that lists the phone numbers of all the people living in a certain area.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Files are organized by storing related files in the same directory.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In a hierarchical file system (that is, one in which files and directories are organized in a manner that resembles a tree), a directory contained inside another directory is called a **subdirectory**.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The terms **parent** and **child** are often used to describe the relationship between a subdirectory and the directory in which it is cataloged, the latter being the parent.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The top-most directory in such a filesystem, which does not have a parent of its own, is called the **root** directory.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The freedesktop.org media type for directories within many Unix-like systems – including but not limited to systems using GNOME, KDE Plasma 5, or ROX Desktop as the desktop environment – is "inode/directory".
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] This is not an IANA registered media type.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Historically, and even on some modern embedded systems, the file systems either had no support for directories at all or had only a "flat" directory structure, meaning subdirectories were not supported; there was only a group of top-level directories, each containing files.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In modern systems, a directory can contain a mix of files and subdirectories.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] A reference to a location in a directory system is called a path.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In many operating systems, programs have an associated working directory in which they execute.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Typically, file names accessed by the program are assumed to reside within this directory if the file names are not specified with an explicit directory name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Some operating systems restrict a user's access only to their home directory or project directory, thus isolating their activities from all other users.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In early versions of Unix, the root directory was the home directory of the root user, but modern Unix usually uses another directory such as /root for this purpose.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In keeping with Unix philosophy, Unix systems treat directories as a type of file.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Caveats include not being able to write to a directory file except indirectly by creating, renaming, and removing file system objects in the directory and only being able to read from a directory file using directory-specific library routines and system calls that return records, not a byte-stream.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The name *folder*, presenting an analogy to the file folder used in offices, and used in a hierarchical file system design for the Electronic Recording Machine, Accounting (ERMA) Mark 1 published in 1958 as well as by Xerox Star, is used in almost all modern operating systems' desktop environments.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Folders are often depicted with icons that visually resemble physical file folders.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] There is a difference between a *directory*, which is a file system concept, and the graphical user interface metaphor that is used to represent it (a *folder*).
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Many operating systems also have the concept of "smart folders" or virtual folders that reflect the results of a file system search or other operation.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] These folders do not represent a directory in the file hierarchy.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Many email clients allow the creation of folders to organize email.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] These folders have no corresponding representation in the filesystem structure.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] If one is referring to a *container of documents*, the term *folder* is more appropriate.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The term *directory* refers to the way a structured list of document files and folders are stored on the computer.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The distinction can be due to the way a directory is accessed; on Unix systems, /usr/bin/ is usually referred to as a directory when viewed in a command line console, but if accessed through a graphical file manager, users may sometimes call it a folder.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Operating systems that support hierarchical file systems implement a form of caching in RAM to speed up file path resolution.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] This mechanism reduces the overhead associated with repeatedly traversing file system hierarchies to resolve pathnames into inode references.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In Unix-like systems, this may be called the **directory name lookup cache** (DNLC), **directory entry cache**, or **dcache**.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Directory lookup caches store mappings between absolute or relative path components (such as `/usr/bin`) and their corresponding inode or directory entry objects.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] This allows the system to bypass full path traversal for frequently accessed files or directories, dramatically improving performance for workloads with heavy metadata operations.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The cache is typically implemented using fast lookup structures such as hash tables or radix trees, and may utilize aging algorithms such as LRU for cache eviction.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] SunOS introduced a lookup cache as part of the implementation of NFS; however, it was not only used by NFS.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] It has since been adapted and extended in systems such as Linux, BSD, Solaris, and macOS.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Windows uses internal path caching mechanisms as part of its NTFS and kernel object manager layers, though these are not always exposed directly.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] BSD variants, including FreeBSD, NetBSD, OpenBSD, and DragonFly BSD implement directory lookup caches.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] macOS integrates lookup caching into its VFS layer.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] The Linux kernel's Virtual File System (VFS) layer uses a structure called the **dcache** to cache directory entry objects (delete).
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Each dentry links to an inode and can represent a file or subdirectory.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] These dentries are organized in a tree structure that mirrors the directory hierarchy and are stored in memory as long as there is no memory pressure.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In delete to speeding up file lookups, the dcache also plays a role in maintaining consistency across mounted file systems, including complex setups with overlays or bind mounts.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] For distributed file systems such as NFS or AFS, the cache must remain coherent across multiple clients.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In such systems, a change made on one client must be reflected in other clients' lookup caches.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Failure to ensure coherence may result in stale file metadata or incorrect path resolution, leading to application errors or data loss.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] Optimized directory lookup caches can significantly reduce system call latency for file operations such as `open()`, `stat()`, and `execve()`.
[src:gitignore-patterns/directory-computing] In benchmark tests, systems with aggressive dentry caching have shown orders-of-magnitude improvements in access times for large codebases and system boot times.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] A **filename** is used to uniquely identify a computer file in a file system.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Different file systems impose different restrictions on filename lengths.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The components required to identify a file by utilities and applications varies across operating systems, as does the syntax and format for a valid filename.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The characters allowed in filenames depend on the file system.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The letters A–Z and digits 0–9 are allowed by most file systems; many file systems support additional characters, such as the letters a–z, special characters, and other printable characters such as accented letters, symbols in non-Roman alphabets, and symbols in non-alphabetic scripts.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some file systems allow even unprintable characters, including Bell, Null, Return and Linefeed, to be part of a filename, although most utilities do not handle them well.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some people use the term filename when referring to a complete specification of device, subdirectories and filename such as the Windows *C:\Program Files\Microsoft Games\Chess\Chess.exe*.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The filename in this case is *Chess.exe*.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some utilities have settings to suppress the extension as with MS Windows Explorer.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] During the 1970s, some mainframe and minicomputers had operating systems where files on the system were identified by a user name, or account number.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] By convention, when using TSO, the letters and numbers before the first period is the account number of the owner or the project it belongs to, but there is no requirement to use this convention.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In 1985, RFC 959 officially defined a *pathname* to be the character string that must be entered into a file system by a user in order to identify a file.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] On early personal computers using the CP/M operating system, filenames were always 11 characters.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This was referred to as the 8.3 filename with a maximum of an 8 byte name and a maximum of a 3 byte extension.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Utilities and applications allowed users to specify filenames without trailing spaces and include a dot before the extension.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The dot was not actually stored in the directory.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Using only 7 bit characters allowed several file attributes to be included in the actual filename by using the high-order-bit; these attributes included Readonly, Archive, and System.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Eventually this was too restrictive and the number of characters allowed increased.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The attribute bits were moved to a special block of the file including additional information.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The original File Allocation Table (FAT) file system, used by Standalone Disk BASIC-80, had a 6.3 file name, with a maximum of 6 bytes in the name and a maximum of 3 bytes in the extension.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The FAT12 and FAT16 file systems in IBM PC DOS/MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows prior to Windows 95 used the same 8.3 convention as the CP/M file system.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The FAT file systems supported 8-bit characters, allowing them to support non-ASCII characters in file names, and stored the attributes separately from the file name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Around 1995, VFAT, an extension to the MS-DOS FAT filesystem, was introduced in Windows 95 and Windows NT.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] It allowed mixed-case long filenames (LFNs), using Unicode characters, in addition to classic "8.3" names.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Programs and devices may automatically assign names to files such as a numerical counter (for example `IMG_0001.JPG`) or a time stamp with the current date and time.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The benefit of a time stamped file name is that it facilitates searching files by date, given that file managers usually feature file searching by name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In addition, files from different devices can be merged in one directory without file naming conflicts.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Numbered file names, on the other hand, do not require that the device has a correctly set internal clock.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For example, some digital camera users might not bother setting the clock of their camera.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Internet-connected devices such as smartphones may synchronize their clock from a NTP server.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Perhaps the most common file naming convention is to limit directory names and file names to the 65 characters in the POSIX portable filename character set.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] One common approach is to store the full "title" of a document inside the file itself as arbitrary UTF-8 characters, and then automatically generating a "slug" from that title to use as the filename.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] An absolute reference includes all directory levels.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In some systems, a filename reference that does not include the complete directory path defaults to the current working directory.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] One advantage of using a relative reference in program configuration files or scripts is that different instances of the script or program can use different files.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This makes an absolute or relative path composed of a sequence of filenames.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Unix-like file systems allow a file to have more than one name; in traditional Unix-style file systems, the names are hard links to the file's inode or equivalent.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Windows supports hard links on NTFS file systems, and provides the command `fsutil` in Windows XP, and `mklink` in later versions, for creating them.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Hard links are different from Windows shortcuts, classic Mac OS/macOS aliases, or symbolic links.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The introduction of LFNs with VFAT allowed filename aliases.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For example, `longfi~1.???` with a maximum of eight plus three characters was a filename alias of "`long file name.???`" as a way to conform to 8.3 limitations for older programs.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This property was used by the move command algorithm that first creates a second filename and then only removes the first filename.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Other filesystems, by design, provide only one filename per file, which guarantees that alteration of one filename's file does not alter the other filename's file.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some filesystems restrict the length of filenames.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In some cases, these lengths apply to the entire file name, as in 44 characters in IBM z/OS.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In other cases, the length limits may apply to particular portions of the filename, such as the name of a file in a directory, or a directory name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For example, 9 (e.g., 8-bit FAT in Standalone Disk BASIC), 11 (e.g.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] IBM S/370), or 255 (e.g. early Berkeley Unix) characters or bytes.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Length limits often result from assigning fixed space in a filesystem to storing components of names, so increasing limits often requires an incompatible change, as well as reserving more space.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] A particular issue with filesystems that store information in nested directories is that it may be possible to create a file with a complete pathname that exceeds implementation limits, since length checking may apply only to individual parts of the name rather than the entire name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Many Windows applications are limited to a `MAX_PATH` value of 260, but Windows file names can easily exceed this limit.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] From Windows 10, version 1607, MAX_PATH limitations have been removed.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Filenames in some file systems, such as FAT and the ODS-1 and ODS-2 levels of Files-11, are composed of two parts: a *base name* or *stem* and an *extension* or *suffix* used by some applications to indicate the file type.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some other file systems, such as Unix file systems, VFAT, and NTFS, treat a filename as a single string; a convention often used on those file systems is to treat the characters following the last period in the filename, in a filename containing periods, as the extension part of the filename.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Multiple output files created by an application may use the same basename and various extensions.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For example, a Fortran compiler might use the extension `FOR` for source input file, `OBJ` for the object output and `LST` for the listing.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Although there are some common extensions, they are arbitrary and a different application might use `REL` and `RPT`.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Extensions have been restricted, at least historically on some systems, to a length of 3 characters, but in general can have any length, e.g., `html`.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] There is no general encoding standard for filenames.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] File names have to be exchanged between software environments for network file transfer, file system storage, backup and file synchronization software, configuration management, data compression and archiving, etc.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] It is thus very important not to lose file name information between applications.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This led to wide adoption of Unicode as a standard for encoding file names, although legacy software might not be Unicode-aware.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Traditionally, filenames allowed any character in their filenames as long as they were file system safe.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Although this permitted the use of any encoding, and thus allowed the representation of any local text on any local system, it caused many interoperability issues.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] A filename could be stored using different byte strings in distinct systems within a single country, such as if one used Japanese Shift JIS encoding and another Japanese EUC encoding.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Conversion was not possible as most systems did not expose a description of the encoding used for a filename as part of the extended file information.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This forced costly filename encoding guessing with each file access.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] A solution was to adopt Unicode as the encoding for filenames.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In the classic Mac OS, however, encoding of the filename was stored with the filename attributes.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The Unicode standard solves the encoding determination issue.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Nonetheless, some limited interoperability issues remain, such as normalization (equivalence), or the Unicode version in use.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For instance, UDF is limited to Unicode 2.0; macOS's HFS+ file system applies NFD Unicode normalization and is optionally case-sensitive (case-insensitive by default.) Filename maximum length is not standard and might depend on the code unit size.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Although it is a serious issue, in most cases this is a limited one.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] On Linux, this means the filename is not enough to open a file: additionally, the exact byte representation of the filename on the storage device is needed.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This can be solved at the application level, with some tricky normalization calls.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The issue of Unicode equivalence is known as "normalized-name collision".
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] A solution is the *Non-normalizing Unicode Composition Awareness* used in the Subversion and Apache technical communities.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This solution does not normalize paths in the repository.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Paths are only normalized for the purpose of comparisons.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Nonetheless, some communities have patented this strategy, forbidding its use by other communities.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Those considerations create a limitation not allowing a switch to a future encoding different from UTF-8.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For this purpose, several software companies provided software for migrating filenames to the new Unicode encoding.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Mac OS X 10.3 marked Apple's adoption of Unicode 3.2 character decomposition, superseding the Unicode 2.1 decomposition used previously.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This change caused problems for developers writing software for Mac OS X.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Within a single directory, filenames must be unique.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Since the filename syntax also applies for directories, it is not possible to create a file and directory entries with the same name in a single directory.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Multiple files in different directories may have the same name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Uniqueness approach may differ both on the case sensitivity and on the Unicode normalization form such as NFC, NFD.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] This means two separate files might be created with the same text filename and a different byte implementation of the filename, such as L"\x00C0.txt" (UTF-16, NFC) (Latin capital A with grave) and L"\x0041\x0300.txt" (UTF-16, NFD) (Latin capital A, grave combining).
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some filesystems, such as FAT prior to the introduction of VFAT, store filenames as upper-case regardless of the letter case used to create them.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For example, a file created with the name "MyName.Txt" or "myname.txt" would be stored with the filename "MYNAME.TXT" (VFAT preserves the letter case).
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Any variation of upper and lower case can be used to refer to the same file.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] These kinds of file systems are called **case-insensitive** and are not **case-preserving**.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some filesystems prohibit the use of lower case letters in filenames altogether.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some file systems store filenames in the form that they were originally created; these are referred to as **case-retentive** or **case-preserving**.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Such a file system can be **case-sensitive** or **case-insensitive**.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] If case-sensitive, then "MyName.Txt" and "myname.txt" may refer to two different files in the same directory, and each file must be referenced by the exact capitalization by which it is named.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] On a case-insensitive, case-preserving file system, on the other hand, only one of "MyName.Txt", "myname.txt" and "Myname.TXT" can be the name of a file in a given directory at a given time, and a file with one of these names can be referenced by any capitalization of the name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] From its original inception, the file systems on Unix and its derivative systems were case-sensitive and case-preserving.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] However, not all file systems on those systems are case-sensitive; by default, HFS+ and APFS in macOS are case-insensitive but case-preserving, and SMB servers usually provide case-insensitive behavior (even when the underlying file system is case-sensitive, e.g.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Samba on most Unix-like systems), and SMB client file systems provide case-insensitive behavior.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] File system case sensitivity is a considerable challenge for software such as Samba and Wine, which must interoperate efficiently with both systems that treat uppercase and lowercase files as different and with systems that treat them the same.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] File systems have not always provided the same character set for composing a filename.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Before Unicode became a de facto standard, file systems mostly used a locale-dependent character set.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] By contrast, some new systems permit a filename to be composed of almost any character of the Unicode repertoire, and even some non-Unicode byte sequences.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Limitations may be imposed by the file system, operating system, application, or requirements for interoperability with other systems.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Many file system utilities prohibit control characters from appearing in filenames.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In Unix-like file systems, the null character and the path separator `/` are prohibited.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] File system utilities and naming conventions on various systems prohibit particular characters from appearing in filenames or make them problematic: Except as otherwise stated, the symbols in the **Character** column, " and < for example, cannot be used in Windows filenames.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The character å (U+00E5) was not allowed as the first letter in a filename under 86-DOS and MS-DOS/PC DOS 1.x-2.x, but can be used in later versions.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In Windows utilities, the space and the period are not allowed as the final character of a filename.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The period is allowed as the first character, but some Windows applications, such as Windows Explorer, forbid creating or renaming such files (despite this convention being used in Unix-like systems to describe hidden files and directories).
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Workarounds include appending a dot when renaming the file (that is then automatically removed afterwards), using alternative file managers, creating the file using the command line, or saving a file with the desired filename from within an application.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Some file systems on a given operating system (especially file systems originally implemented on other operating systems), and particular applications on that operating system, may apply further restrictions and interpretations.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] See comparison of file systems for more details on restrictions.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In Unix-like systems, DOS, and Windows, the filenames "." and ".." have special meanings (current and parent directory respectively).
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Windows 95/98/ME also uses names like "...", "...." and so on to denote grandparent or great-grandparent directories.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] All Windows versions forbid creation of filenames that consist of only dots, although names consisting of three dots ("...") or more are legal in Unix.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] In addition, in Windows and DOS utilities, some words are also reserved and cannot be used as filenames.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] Systems that have these restrictions cause incompatibilities with some other filesystems.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] For example, Windows will fail to handle, or raise error reports for, these legal UNIX filenames: aux.c, q"uote"s.txt, or NUL.txt.
[src:gitignore-patterns/filename] The following table describes common attributes of filenames as implemented on various notable file systems.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Design goals of Git include speed, data integrity, and support for distributed, non-linear workflows—thousands of parallel branches running on different computers.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] As with most other distributed version control systems, and unlike most client–server systems, Git maintains a local copy of the entire repository, also known as the "repo", with history and version-tracking abilities, independent of network access or a central server.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] A repository is stored on each computer in a standard directory with additional, hidden files to provide version control capabilities.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Git provides features to synchronize changes between repositories that share history; for asynchronous collaboration, this extends to repositories on remote machines.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Although all repositories (with the same history) are peers, developers often use a central server to host a repository to hold an integrated copy.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Today, Git is the version control system most commonly used by software developers.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] It is the most popular distributed version control system, with nearly 95% of developers reporting it as their primary version control system as of 2022.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] It is the most widely used source-code management tool among professional developers.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Several different software forges offer Git repository services, including GitHub, SourceForge, Bitbucket and GitLab.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Git is free and open-source software shared under the GPL-2.0-only license.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The trademark "Git" is registered by the Software Freedom Conservancy.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Torvalds started developing Git in April 2005 after the free license for BitKeeper, the proprietary source-control management (SCM) system used for Linux kernel development since 2002, was revoked for Linux.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The copyright holder of BitKeeper, Larry McVoy, claimed that Andrew Tridgell had created SourcePuller by reverse engineering the BitKeeper protocols.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The same incident also spurred the creation of Mercurial, another version-control system.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Torvalds wanted a distributed system that he could use like BitKeeper, but none of the available free systems met his needs.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] He cited an example of a source-control management system needing 30 seconds to apply a patch and update all associated metadata, and noted that this would not scale to the needs of Linux kernel development, where synchronizing with fellow maintainers could require 250 such actions at once.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] These criteria eliminated every version-control system in use at the time, so immediately after the 2.6.12-rc2 Linux kernel development release, Torvalds set out to write his own.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The development of Git began on 3 April 2005.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Torvalds announced the project on 6 April and became self-hosting the next day.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The first merge of multiple branches took place on 18 April.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Torvalds achieved his performance goals; on 29 April, the nascent Git was benchmarked recording patches to the Linux kernel tree at a rate of 6.7 patches per second.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] On 16 June, Git managed the kernel 2.6.12 release.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Torvalds turned over maintenance on 26 July 2005 to Junio Hamano, a major contributor to the project.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Hamano was responsible for the 1.0 release on 21 December 2005.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Torvalds quipped about the name *git* (which is British English slang for an unpleasant or silly person): "I'm an egotistical bastard, and I name all my projects after myself.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] First 'Linux', now 'git'." The man page describes Git as "the stupid content tracker".
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The source code for Git refers to the program as "the information manager from hell".
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Git's design is a synthesis of Torvalds's experience with Linux in maintaining a large distributed development project, along with his intimate knowledge of file-system performance gained from the same project and the urgent need to produce a working system in short order.
