[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Each object is identified by a SHA-1 hash of its contents.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Git computes the hash and uses this value for the object's name.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The object is put into a directory matching the first two characters of its hash.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The rest of the hash is used as the file name for that object.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Git stores each revision of a file as a unique blob.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] The relationships between the blobs can be found through examining the tree and commit objects.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Newly added objects are stored in their entirety using zlib compression.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] This can consume a large amount of disk space quickly, so objects can be combined into *packs*, which use delta compression to save space, storing blobs as their changes relative to other blobs.
[src:gitignore-patterns/git] Additionally, Git stores labels called refs (short for references) to indicate the locations of various commits.
